  "signature": "ed25519:b2d4f6a8c1e3b5d7f9a2c4e6b8d0f2a4c6e8b0d2f4a6c8e0b2d4f6a8c1e3b5d7",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/sqa-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2022 R2 is a commercially validated FEA solver with ISO 9001 certification and documented V&V test suite. FDA's in-house Python pre/post-processing scripts are version-controlled in a Git repository with peer-reviewed commit history. DePuy Synthes provided solver configuration files under their design-control QMS. Gradation 3 achieved: all three modeling groups maintain formal SQA procedures with documented test plans, version control, and change management exceeding the Gradation 2 minimum requirement of version-controlled code with documented testing."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/code-verification-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical passes the NAFEMS benchmark suite (LE1, LE10, LE11, FV52) with documented agreement to analytical solutions within 0.5%. Patch test and Taylor series convergence tests were executed for the specific element formulations (SOLID186, CONTA174) used in this model. All three modeling groups independently verified their implementations against the same NAFEMS benchmarks, achieving consistent results. Gradation 3 achieved through use of multiple independent verification benchmarks spanning relevant loading modes."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/discretization-gradation3",
      "rationale": "Mesh convergence studies were performed by each of the three modeling groups independently. Reported GCI values for stiffness QoI range from 0.8% to 2.1% across the ensemble, all below the 5% threshold. Element size was systematically halved across three refinement levels; Richardson extrapolation confirmed asymptotic convergence. The titanium screw shank and the polyethylene block interface were identified as critical regions and received additional refinement. Gradation 3 achieved: formal GCI-based discretization error estimation with documented convergence in all three models."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorStatus": "not-applicable",
      "rationale": "Numerical solver error as defined in ASME V&V 40 Section 5.3.4 encompasses iterative convergence error arising from implicit nonlinear solvers that require user-specified convergence tolerances (e.g., Newton-Raphson residual norms). This factor is applicable when iterative solution of a nonlinear algebraic system introduces solution-dependent truncation that must be distinguished from discretization error. In the present COU, all three FEA models employ a geometrically linear elastic formulation for the titanium construct under ASTM F1717 loading, which remains well within the small-deformation regime for the stiffness and yield-force QoIs. The governing linear algebraic system K·u = F is solved via a direct sparse factorization method (PARDISO within Ansys; SuperLU within the FDA implementation) with machine-precision residuals. There is no iterative convergence loop, no user-set tolerance, and no iterative residual that could constitute a separable numerical solver error. The borderline consideration was whether the contact formulation at the screw-block interface introduces a nonlinear iteration requiring convergence assessment; however, the augmented Lagrangian contact algorithm converges in a single augmentation step at the applied load levels (confirmed by augmentation history logs from all three modeling groups), making the iterative residual negligible relative to discretization error already quantified under the Discretization Error factor. Therefore, Numerical Solver Error is scoped out as not-applicable for this COU."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/use-error-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Model setup procedures were documented in a formal simulation protocol reviewed by all three modeling groups prior to execution. Boundary conditions, material assignments, contact definitions, and load application were specified in a shared protocol document with explicit tolerances. Each group performed an independent cross-check of the other groups' model inputs against the protocol. Discrepancies identified during cross-check (two minor contact stiffness parameter differences) were resolved and documented. Gradation 2 achieved: documented setup procedures with independent peer review of model configuration."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-form-gradation3",
      "rationale": "Linear elastic continuum mechanics is the governing model form. Titanium alloy Ti-6Al-4V is modeled as isotropic linear elastic (E = 114 GPa, ν = 0.34) consistent with published material data and ASTM standards. The polyethylene vertebral body surrogate is modeled as linear elastic (E = 1.1 GPa, ν = 0.46) calibrated to the specific UHMWPE block lot used in testing. Model form uncertainty was assessed by comparing FEA predictions against the experimental ensemble: all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm) fall within the 10% acceptance band with E/uval < 1.96. Sensitivity analyses confirm that the linear elastic assumption is valid for the pre-yield loading regime. Gradation 3 achieved through quantitative comparison of model form predictions against experimental data with uncertainty-normalized error metrics."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/model-inputs-gradation3",
      "rationale": "Material properties were measured from the same lot of Ti-6Al-4V and UHMWPE used in physical testing. Tensile coupon data (n=5 per material) provided mean and standard deviation for E and ν. Geometric inputs were derived from CMM measurements of the actual test constructs (n=11), with dimensional tolerances propagated through the FEA ensemble. Sensitivity analysis (one-at-a-time and Morris screening) identified elastic modulus of the screw as the dominant input; a full probabilistic propagation using Latin hypercube sampling (N=500) was performed for this parameter. Input uncertainty contributions were quantified and included in the combined uncertainty budget. Gradation 3 achieved: probabilistic input uncertainty propagation with measured material properties from test lot."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-samples-gradation3",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs tested across two independent laboratories (Lab 1: n=6; Lab 2: n=5). All constructs used production-representative non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screws from the same manufacturing lot (Lot 2021-NC-75-A). UHMWPE vertebral body surrogates were machined from the same billet per ASTM F1717 specifications. CMM measurements confirm all constructs are within dimensional specification. Inter-laboratory variability was characterized and found to be within experimental uncertainty bounds. Sample-to-sample variability is explicitly included in the uncertainty budget. Gradation 3 achieved: documented sample characterization with inter-laboratory reproducibility assessment."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/test-conditions-gradation2",
      "rationale": "Testing was conducted under a single load configuration (pure compression-bending per ASTM F1717 fixture geometry) at a single displacement rate (5 mm/min) and ambient temperature (23 ± 2°C). While the test conditions are well-characterized and reproducible, only one test condition was evaluated, limiting the ability to characterize model behavior across the range of potential COU loading environments. Gradation 2 achieved rather than the required Gradation 3. This known gap is accepted because: (1) ASTM F1717 is the regulatory standard test method for this device class, (2) the single condition represents the worst-case loading scenario per the standard, and (3) model influence is Medium with confirmatory testing, making the risk of this gap acceptable at the Medium assurance level. This factor is identified as a limitation in the decision record."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/equivalency-gradation3",
      "rationale": "A formal equivalency mapping was performed between the physical test inputs and the FEA model inputs. Fixture geometry was measured via CMM and replicated in the FEA boundary condition definitions with documented tolerances. Applied displacement boundary conditions in FEA match the test machine crosshead displacement to within 0.1 mm. Material properties in the FEA are directly measured from the test lot. Contact conditions at the screw-rod and screw-block interfaces are documented and mapped to the physical assembly torque specifications. Equivalency was verified by an independent reviewer not involved in model construction. Gradation 3 achieved: documented one-to-one mapping of all significant physical inputs to model inputs with independent verification."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 4,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/output-comparison-gradation3",
      "rationale": "Quantitative comparison performed using the ASME V&V 40 validation metric E/uval for each QoI. Stiffness: E/uval = 0.84 (mean FEA 312 N/mm vs. mean experimental 318 N/mm; combined uncertainty 7.1 N/mm). Yield force: E/uval = 1.12 (mean FEA 1847 N vs. mean experimental 1821 N; combined uncertainty 23.2 N). Force at 40 mm: E/uval = 1.31 (mean FEA 2103 N vs. mean experimental 2071 N; combined uncertainty 24.4 N). All three QoIs satisfy E/uval < 1.96 and percentage difference < 10%. Uncertainty budget includes model input uncertainty, discretization error, experimental measurement uncertainty, and inter-laboratory variability. Gradation 4 achieved: full uncertainty-normalized validation metric with complete uncertainty budget across all three QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/qoi-relevance-gradation3",
      "rationale": "The three QoIs (construct stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) are directly specified in ASTM F1717 as the required reporting quantities for pedicle screw construct testing. These QoIs map directly to the clinical performance requirements: stiffness governs load sharing with the vertebral column, yield force defines the onset of permanent deformation, and force at 40 mm characterizes post-yield energy absorption relevant to fatigue loading scenarios. The COU decision (demonstrate FEA reproduces experimental behavior) is directly supported by these QoIs. Gradation 3 achieved: QoIs are regulatory-standard quantities with documented mapping to clinical performance requirements and COU decision needs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/criteria/validation-relevance-gradation3",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: the same FEA modeling framework, same device geometry, same material system, same loading configuration (ASTM F1717 compression-bending), and same QoIs used in the COU are used in the validation. The validation is not a surrogate or analogous activity — it is a direct comparison of the FEA predictions against physical testing of the same construct type. The two-laboratory design strengthens the generalizability of the validation finding. The only gap between validation and COU is the single test condition (addressed under Test Conditions factor). Gradation 3 achieved: direct validation with the same model, device, and loading as the COU, with documented mapping of any gaps."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/decision/cou1-noncannulated-accepted-2026",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/nagaraja/org/fda-cdrh-osel",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The FEA model ensemble for the non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw construct is accepted as credible for the stated COU at Medium assurance level. Twelve of thirteen V&V 40 factors were formally assessed; one factor (Numerical Solver Error) was determined not-applicable with documented technical rationale (direct sparse solver with no iterative convergence loop). Of the twelve assessed factors, eleven achieved or exceeded their required gradation level. The single factor below required level (Test Conditions, achieved Gradation 2 vs. required Gradation 3) reflects the use of a single ASTM F1717 test condition; this gap is accepted because ASTM F1717 is the regulatory standard method representing the design-critical loading scenario, and the Medium model influence with confirmatory physical testing provides sufficient assurance that the single-condition limitation does not undermine the credibility conclusion. Quantitative validation results demonstrate E/uval < 1.96 and percentage differences < 10% for all three QoIs (stiffness, yield force, force at 40 mm displacement) across N=11 constructs from two independent laboratories, with a complete uncertainty budget including model input uncertainty, discretization error (GCI < 2.1%), experimental measurement uncertainty, and inter-laboratory variability. The three-group FEA ensemble (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes) provides additional confidence through independent model construction with consistent predictions. The credibility evidence is sufficient to support use of this FEA framework for regulatory decision-making regarding the non-cannulated pedicle screw design.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
